body:
I tried this code:

main.rs
```rust
#![feature(extern_types)]

use libc::{LC_ALL, setlocale, c_int, c_char};

extern "C" {
    pub type WINDOW;
    pub fn initscr() -> *mut WINDOW;
    pub fn cbreak() -> c_int;
    pub fn noecho() -> c_int;
    pub fn keypad(arg1: *mut WINDOW, arg2: bool) -> c_int;
    pub static mut stdscr: *mut WINDOW;
    pub fn clear() -> c_int;
    #[link_name = "\u{1}move"]
    pub fn move_(arg1: c_int, arg2: c_int) -> c_int;
    pub fn insnstr(arg1: *const c_char, arg2: c_int) -> c_int;
    pub fn getch() -> c_int;
    pub fn endwin() -> c_int;
}

fn main() {
    unsafe {
        Some(()).unwrap();
        setlocale(LC_ALL, b"\0".as_ptr() as _);
        initscr();
        cbreak(); 
        noecho(); 
        keypad(stdscr, true);
        clear();
        move_(10, 10);
        insnstr("П".as_ptr() as _, 2);
        getch();
        endwin();
    }
}
```
with Cargo.toml:
```
[package]
name = "test_ncurses"
version = "0.1.0"
edition = "2018"

[build-dependencies]
pkg-config = "0.3.18"

[dependencies]
libc = "0.2.27"
```

and build.rs:
```rust
fn main() {
    println!("cargo:rerun-if-env-changed=PKG_CONFIG_PATH");
    pkg_config::Config::new()
        .atleast_version("5.0")
        .probe("ncursesw")
        .unwrap();
    println!("cargo:rustc-link-lib=ncursesw");
}
```

When I execute `cargo run` command, I expected to see alone cyrillic letter "П" on screen. Instead I see two letters: "Пc".

If I remove "Some(()).unwrap();" (the only place using Rust `std`) from main program, the effect disappears. If I remove pkg-config invoke from build.rs, the effect disappears also.

`rustc --version --verbose`:
```
rustc 1.46.0-nightly (0c03aee8b 2020-07-05)
binary: rustc
commit-hash: 0c03aee8b81185d65b5821518661c30ecdb42de5
commit-date: 2020-07-05
host: x86_64-unknown-freebsd
release: 1.46.0-nightly
LLVM version: 10.0
```

P.S. You can see more garbage letters with another string:

```rust
let t = "👩Привет, world!👩‍🔬";
insnstr(t.as_ptr() as _, t.len() as _);
 ```

produces
```
👩Привет, world!👩 🔬called `Option::u
```
